# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-stieglitz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The gallery is recognized for two achievements: First, its exhibitions helped bring art photography to the same stature in America as painting and sculpture.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Pioneering artistic photographers such as Stieglitz, Edward Steichen, Alvin Langdon Coburn, Gertrude Käsebier and Clarence H.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] White all gained critical recognition through exhibitions at 291.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Equally important, Stieglitz used this space to introduce to the United States some of the most avant-garde European artists of the time, including Henri Matisse, Auguste Rodin, Henri Rousseau, Paul Cézanne, Pablo Picasso, Constantin Brâncuși, Marcel Duchamp, and the Dadaist Francis Picabia.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] At the beginning of the 20th century photography's place in the world of fine art was still very indefinite.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Although there had been major exhibitions of photography in the Europe and in the U.S., all of them had been judged by painters and sculptors.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Photographers were not considered "real" artists, even though many photographers had won awards in international salons.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz himself had won over 150 awards throughout the world by the end of the 1890s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz had hoped to elevate the position of photography by convincing the New York Camera Club to allow him to put together a panel of photographers who would then be the sole judges of a photography competition.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] After more than a year of arguing with the directors of the Camera Club, many of whom did not have any passion for photography as art, Stieglitz gave up and began looking for other forums.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In late 1900 he met Edward Steichen, who had been trained as a painter but who had also taken up photography.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Steichen shared the enthusiasm and passion of Stieglitz, and soon the two were planning how to change the course of photography in America.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] By the following year they had conceived of a great exhibition of photography, the first to be judged by photographers themselves, and had found a venue at the National Arts Club in New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In March 1902, an exhibition of "American Pictorial Photography, arranged by The Photo-Secession" opened to critical acclaim.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Moreover, Stieglitz had met his goal of having a show judged by photographers since, in spite of the title of the show, by all accounts he was the sole person responsible for selecting the exhibitors.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The following year Stieglitz further cemented his reputation as the leading proponent of fine art photography by launching the famed journal *Camera Work* with the assistance of his friend and fellow photographer Joseph Keiley.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Rather than be daunted by this setback, Stieglitz became even more convinced that he would succeed in convincing the art world of the rightful place of photography if he could only find the right platform for his message.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] By the end of 1904 Stieglitz was in a difficult position.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Curtis Bell, president of the American Federation of Photography and an outspoken critic of Stieglitz, organized an exhibition called "The First American Photographic Salon" at the Clausen Galleries in New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] It was judged by a jury of eminent American painters, including William Merritt Chase and Robert Henri, which gave it considerable standing in the art world.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz and other photographers saw it as a direct challenge to Stieglitz's reputation, which it was clearly intended to be.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz countered this move by trying to get some of the best known photographers of Europe to join him as part of a united front.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He traveled to London to meet with some of the founders of the important photographic group The Linked Ring, including J.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Evans, Alvin Langdon Coburn and Alfred Horley Hinton.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He was hoping to convince them to start a chapter of the Linked Ring in the United States, which he would direct.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He also met with playwright George Bernard Shaw, who was an avid amateur photographer, about ways to promote photography as an art form.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz took ill before any of these conversations led to anything, and he had to return home.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He was tired, frustrated and seeking a definitive new way to carry out his mission of promoting photography for photography's sake – independent of any other art form.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] When Stieglitz returned to New York in 1905 Edward Steichen was living in a studio apartment on the top (fifth) floor of a small building at 291 Fifth Avenue, between 30th and 31st Streets on the East side of the avenue.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Steichen noticed that some rooms across from him were vacant, and he soon convinced Stieglitz that they would make a perfect space to exhibit photography and in particular the works of the Photo-Secession.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz, who was still dejected from his trip to Europe, was reluctant at first, but Steichen persisted.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] By summer Stieglitz signed a one-year lease for three small rooms that would soon become one of the most famous art galleries in the world.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The two of them began planning how to use the new space most effectively, not only as a gallery but as an educational facility for artists and photographers and as a meeting place for art lovers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] On November 24, 1905, the Little Galleries of the Photo-Secession formally opened its doors, with almost no public notice.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The opening was attended mainly by those members of the Photo-Secession who were in New York at the time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The first exhibit consisted of one hundred prints by Photo-Secession members, selected entirely by Stieglitz.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Over the next few weeks hundreds of New Yorkers came to the gallery, and Stieglitz was once again elevated to the position of standard bearer of artistic photographer in America.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The opening show was followed in January, 1906, by one of French photographers, including Robert Demachy, Constant Puyo and René Le Bégue, all of whom showed prints made by the gum bichromate process.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] This was followed by a two-person show of the works of Gertrude Käsebier and Clarence H.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Four more exhibitions were held in 1906, including one of British photographers, early prints by Steichen, a show devoted to German and Austrian photographers, and another exhibition of prints by members of the Photo-Secession.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] After a highly successful first year, Stieglitz and Steichen felt that they had made their point about the stature of fine art photography.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] So confident were they of their success that their colleague Joseph Keily wrote "today in America the real battle for the recognition of pictorial photography is over.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] If there was any truth to this statement it reflected directly back at Stieglitz since he was known for his authoritarian control of the Photo-Secession and in selecting what was exhibited at the gallery.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Until now Stieglitz's discomfort was held in check by Steichen's more conservative nature, but in the summer of 1906 Steichen decided to move to Paris in order to devote more of his time to his photography and painting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Without Steichen's business eye watching over him, Stieglitz began to reclaim some of his radical roots.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz decided to shake things up, and he did so by mounting the first non-photography show at the gallery in January, 1907.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] This is notable because it signaled the beginning of Stieglitz's role as a pioneer promoter of modern art in America.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The show, drawings by artist Pamela Colman Smith, initially attracted little attention, but after a prominent critic praised the work it became the best attended exhibition to date.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] A substantial number of the works were sold, and interest in the show was so strong that it had to be extended eight days.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz began planning for future non-photography shows, but for the remainder of 1907 the walls were filled with exhibits by such photographers as Adolf de Meyer, Alvin Langdon Coburn and, once again, members of the Photo-Secession.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In the meantime, Steichen had become friends with the famous sculptor Auguste Rodin in Paris, and he convinced Rodin to lend him some of his drawings for a show at the gallery in New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The 1908 gallery season started with the show "Drawings by Auguste Rodin", the first exhibit in the United States of his works on paper.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Soon after that show ended Stieglitz was notified that the landlord wanted to double the rent and would require a four-year lease.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] At that time the Photo-Secession as a group had only a small income, no more than US$400 per year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In spite of minor successes, the original plan that membership fees and commissions would support the gallery had not been realized.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Although he appealed to those members that he knew, the economy was in a significant downturn and no offers of assistance appeared.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Since there was no other source of income, Stieglitz sadly went about closing the gallery.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] By April of that year the original gallery space had been emptied.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] It was immediately taken over by a ladies' tailor shop.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] After some convincing by Haviland that the new space was workable, Stieglitz gathered some other friends and came up with additional funds for utilities, supplies, printing and framing.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The new gallery space, which measured only fifteen feet square, was actually located in the next building on the block at 293 Fifth Avenue.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The wall between the two buildings had been removed during a previous renovation, however, so by all appearances the new gallery seemed to share the same address as the old one.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Perhaps to save money on printing and perhaps because of his affection for the old gallery, Stieglitz wanted the new address to remain "291".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Both Haviland and he, however, agreed that the previous name of "Little Galleries of the Photo-Secession" was no longer appropriate.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] They wanted the new space to be about more than photography.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Later, Stieglitz would write "We are dealing, not with a society, not with an organization, as much as with a movement.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] From thenceforth Stieglitz referred to the gallery as "291", without the street name or other descriptive title.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] However, some of the original members of the Photo-Secession did not appreciate the name change and especially the thinking that led to it.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz's old friends Gertrude Käsebier and Clarence H.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] White saw it as the last straw in a series of autocratic moves by Stieglitz, and soon a series of increasingly bitter arguments broke out among the three of them.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] At one point Stieglitz wrote "To my dismay, jealousies soon became rampant among photographers around me, an exact repetition of the situation I rebelled against at the Camera Club.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Various Secessionists were in danger of harming not only each other but what I was attempting to build and demonstrate.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Meanwhile, Steichen returned to the U.S. in February 1908 with a new group of photos for a show to be held at the gallery the following month.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] More importantly, he brought with him a group of prints lent to him by Henri Matisse, who at that time little known outside France.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz promptly assembled the prints for a show in the new space.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] It was the first show of any work by Matisse in the United States and the first one-man show for the artist outside of Paris, and it marked the turning point in the focus of the gallery.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] After this show, 291 was known much less for photography and much more as a leading force for modern art in America.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Moreover, Stieglitz continued to make sure that the gallery was not just an exhibition space; he strongly believed in its original mission as being an educational facility and meeting place for those with avant-garde ideas.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Describing the Matisse exhibition, he wrote "Here was the work of a new man, with new ideas – a very anarchist, it seemed, in art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In addition to marking the beginning of a new path for 291, 1909 was significant for Stieglitz due to the death of his father in May.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The two had not been particularly close, but in his will, Stieglitz's father left him the then substantial amount of $10,000.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz drew on this amount over the next several years to help keep 291 in business.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The new art and the public's reactions to it were very vitalizing to Stieglitz; it gave him a brand new set of admirers and followers at a time when he was feeling less and less connected to his old colleagues at the Photo-Secession.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] From then on, the course of the gallery was set.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] From 1909 until it closed in 1917, 291 featured only six shows of photography out of a total of 61 exhibitions held.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The change in the focus of the gallery led to a coalescence of group of intellectuals and artists who both sympathized with Stieglitz's aims and who themselves were invigorated by the atmosphere there.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] After the artistic success of the Matisse exhibit, the gallery took on a new life.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] De Zayas had both a passion and a vision that matched with Stieglitz's personality, and soon he was helping define what the aesthetics of this new generation of art would be.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] His work was exhibited at the gallery, he wrote several articles for *Camera Work*, and he introduced Stieglitz to some of the newest European artists by serving as a guide and interpreter when Stieglitz would travel to Europe.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] His interest in African tribal art and admiration for Picasso's Cubist work convinced Stieglitz to hold groundbreaking exhibitions of these subjects at 291.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] For historical context, virtually no other galleries in the United States were showing works with such abstract and dynamic content at that time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In fact, the more an artist confounded the public the more Stieglitz felt justified in his efforts.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Among the significant exhibitions that took place during this period were first shows for Alfred Maurer, John Marin and Marsden Hartley, second shows of Rodin and Matisse, and important shows for newer artists Arthur Carles, Arthur Dove and Max Weber.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Starting in 1913 Stieglitz began to express an increasing amount of frustration over the changes that were happening in the world at that time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He wrote "Much of the enthusiasm that had existed at 291 gradually disappeared because of the coming war.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Close friends seemed to fall by the wayside." Stieglitz was especially troubled because his parents came from Germany, and he still had many close friends there.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] While he did not sympathize with the German war efforts, he "could not see Germany as all wrong and the Allies as all right.".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] At the same time, because of the depressed economy attendance at the gallery sharply declined and subscriptions to *Camera Work* dropped off.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] To make matters even worse, the small corps of volunteer workers at the gallery all but disappeared as people joined the armed forces or had to take on other jobs to help make ends meet.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Once again it was Haviland who came to the rescue.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In early 1915 he told Stieglitz that 291 was in a rut, and something bold was needed to bring it back again.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He assembled a close circle of relatively well-off friends, including Agnes Meyer and Dorothy Norman, and together with Stieglitz they came up with the idea of publishing a new magazine.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] They decided that this time it would be not only a magazine about art but a work of art itself, printed in a limited edition with very high quality paper and reproductions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The new magazine, which they all agreed should be called *291*, appeared in March, 1915, to critical acclaim.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Twelve issues of *291* were printed over the next fourteen months, showcasing some of the most avant-garde art and design of the times.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The magazine did little to revive the status of the gallery.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Stieglitz continued to present some outstanding shows, but the overall effect of the mounting war tension on the economy could not be overcome.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In the early years of their relationship O'Keeffe was an inspiration for Stieglitz's photography and a source of creative energy.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Other male gallery owners at this time did not commonly seek out or display women's artwork, however, Stieglitz's believed in the legitimacy of females as artists and included Georgia's work in many group exhibitions, and in individual exhibition of her work on April 3, 1917.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] However his advertisement of O'Keeffe's work at his gallery and his representation of her as an artist was in a large part for her femininity and its presence in her work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In June, 1917, only two months after the United States declared war on Germany, Stieglitz closed *291*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] He made a photograph called *The Last Days of 291* (National Gallery of Art, Alfred Stieglitz Collection) which symbolized his feelings at the time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] It depicts a model of a young soldier, armed with a sword and a broom, protecting works of art behind him.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] To his side is an older, bandaged warrior looking on, possibly representing Stieglitz himself as someone who had been wounded in the battle to protect the art that must now be guarded by a new generation.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Later Stieglitz would return to New York to run two more galleries.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] From 1925 until 1929 he directed the Intimate Gallery, showcasing the work of American artists, including Marsden Hartley, Arthur Dove, John Marin, Paul Strand, Charles Demuth, and Georgia O'Keeffe, who by then had become his wife.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In 1929 he opened "An American Place", where he presented the work of the *Seven Americans* (Hartley, Marin, Dove, Demuth, O'Keeffe, Strand and Stieglitz) until his death in 1946.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In 1914 Stieglitz published a series of responses to the question "What is 291?" in an issue of *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Eugene Meyer responded with a free-form poem.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Kerfoot: "291 is greater than the sum of all its definitions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] For it is a living force, working for both good and evil.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Marsden Hartley: "A pure instrument is certainly sure to give forth pure sound.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] Over the gallery's 13-year existence, the exhibitions held there included an impressive list of firsts in both photography and modern art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] In 1917, Francis Picabia founded the magazine *391* in Barcelona, the title inspired by *291*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/291-art-gallery] The definitive source book for 291 and the exhibitions held there is Sarah Greenough's massive *Modern Art and America: Alfred Stieglitz and His New York Galleries* (Washington: National Gallery of Art, 2000).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-storm] The painting is part of a collection of work depicting sea- and landscapes of Maine or Lake George, and were created by O'Keeffe between 1921 and 1922.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-storm] The technique and style of *A Storm* reflects O'Keeffe's earlier preference for charcoal as a medium.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-storm] It was donated to the Metropolitan Museum of Art by a private collector in 1981.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat's composition, painted on a large canvas, includes a number of Parisians at a park on the banks of the River Seine.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] It is held in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Georges Seurat painted *A Sunday Afternoon* between May 1884 and March 1885, and from October 1885 to May 1886, focusing meticulously on the landscape of the park and concentrating on issues of colour, light, and form.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The painting is approximately 2 by 3 metres (6.6 ft × 9.8 ft) in size.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat completed numerous preliminary drawings and oil sketches before completing his masterpiece.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] One complete painting, the study featured to the right, measures 27 3/4 x 41 in.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] (70.5 x 104.1 cm) and is on display in the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Inspired by optical effects and perception inherent in the color theories of Michel Eugène Chevreul, Ogden Rood and others, Seurat adapted this scientific research to his painting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat contrasted miniature dots or small brushstrokes of colors that when unified optically in the human eye were perceived as a single shade or hue.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] He believed that this form of painting, called Divisionism at the time (a term he preferred) but now known as Pointillism, would make the colors more brilliant and powerful than standard brushstrokes.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The use of dots of almost uniform size came in the second year of his work on the painting, 1885–86.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The Island of la Grande Jatte is located at the very gates of Paris, lying in the Seine between Neuilly and Levallois-Perret, a short distance from where La Défense business district currently stands.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Although for many years it was an industrial site, it has become the site of a public garden and a housing development.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] When Seurat began the painting in 1884, the island was a bucolic retreat far from the urban center.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The painting was first exhibited at the eighth (and last) Impressionist exhibition in May 1886, then in August 1886, dominating the second Salon of the Société des Artistes Indépendants, of which Seurat had been a founder in 1884.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat was extremely disciplined, always serious, and private to the point of secretiveness—for the most part, steering his own steady course.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] As a painter, he wanted to make a difference in the history of art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] With *La Grande Jatte*, Seurat was immediately acknowledged as the leader of a new and rebellious form of Impressionism called Neo-Impressionism.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat's painting was a mirror impression of his own painting, *Bathers at Asnières*, completed shortly before, in 1884.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Whereas the bathers in that earlier painting are doused in light, almost every figure on *La Grande Jatte* appears to be cast in the shadow, either under trees or an umbrella, or from another person.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] For Parisians, Sunday was the day to escape the heat of the city and head for the shade of the trees and the cool breezes that came off the river.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] And at first glance, the viewer sees many different people relaxing in a park by the river.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] On the right, a fashionable couple, the woman with the sunshade and the man in his top hat, are on a stroll.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] On the left, another woman who is also well dressed extends her fishing pole over the water.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] There is a small man with the black hat and thin cane looking at the river, and a white dog with a brown head, a woman knitting, a man playing a trumpet, two soldiers standing at attention as the musician plays, and a woman hunched under an orange umbrella.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat also painted a man with a pipe, a woman under a parasol in a boat filled with rowers, and a couple admiring their infant child.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Some of the characters are doing curious things.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The lady on the right side has a pet monkey on a leash.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] A lady on the left near the river bank is fishing.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The area was known at the time as being a place to procure prostitutes among the bourgeoisie, a likely allusion of the otherwise odd "fishing" rod.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the painting's center stands a little girl dressed in white (who is not in a shadow), who stares directly at the viewer of the painting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] This may be interpreted as someone who is silently questioning the audience.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the 1950s, historian and Marxist philosopher Ernst Bloch drew social and political significance from Seurat's *La Grande Jatte*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The historian's focal point was what he saw as Seurat's mechanical use of the figures and what their static nature said about French society at the time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Afterward, critique of the work often centered on the artist's presumed mathematical and robotic interpretation of the meaning of modernity in Paris.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The border of the painting is, unusually, in inverted color, as if the world around them is also slowly inverting from the way of life they have known.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seen in this context, the boy who bathes on the other side of the river bank at Asnières appears to be calling out to them, as if to say, "We are the future.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat painted the *La Grande Jatte* in three distinct stages.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the first stage, which was started in 1884, he mixed his paints from several individual pigments and was still using dull earth pigments such as ochre or burnt sienna.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the second stage, during 1885 and 1886, Seurat dispensed with the earth pigments and also limited the number of individual pigments in his paints.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] This change in his palette was due to his application of the advanced color theories of his time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] His intention was to paint small dots or strokes of pure color that would then mix on the retina of the beholder to achieve the desired color impression instead of the usual practice of mixing individual pigments.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat's palette consisted of the usual pigments of his time such as cobalt blue, emerald green and vermilion.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Additionally, he used the then new pigment zinc yellow (zinc chromate), predominantly for yellow highlights in the sunlit grass in the middle of the painting but also in mixtures with orange and blue pigments.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the century and more since the painting's completion, the zinc yellow has darkened to brown—a color degeneration that was already showing in the painting in Seurat's lifetime.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The discoloration of the originally bright yellow zinc yellow (zinc chromate) to a brownish color is due to the chemical reaction of the chromate ions to orange-colored dichromate ions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the third stage during 1888–89 Seurat added the colored borders to his composition.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The results of investigation into the discoloration of this painting have been combined with further research into natural aging of paints to digitally rejuvenate the painting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In 1923, Frederic Bartlett was appointed trustee of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] He and his second wife, Helen Birch Bartlett, loaned their collection of French Post-Impressionist and Modernist art to the museum.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Bartlett who had an interest in French and avant-garde artists and influenced her husband's collecting tastes.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] *Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte* was purchased on the advice of the Art Institute of Chicago's curatorial staff in 1924.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In conceptual artist Don Celender's 1974–75 book *Observation and Scholarship Examination for Art Historians, Museum Directors, Artists, Dealers and Collectors*, it is claimed that the institute paid $24,000 for the work (over $354,000 in 2018 dollars).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In 1958, the painting was loaned for the only time, to the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] On 15 April 1958, a fire there, which killed one person on the second floor of the museum, forced the emergency evacuation of the painting, which had been on a floor above the fire, to the Whitney Museum, which adjoined MoMA at the time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Once at the institute, the painting was shown in a variety of framing styles and colors over the years.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Then in 2022, a new frame was built that attempted to match as closely as possible what conservators felt was Seurat's most likely intent.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The painting is the basis for the 1984 Broadway musical *Sunday in the Park with George* by Stephen Sondheim and James Lapine, which tells a fictionalized story of the painting's creation.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Subsequently, the painting is sometimes referred to by the misnomer "*Sunday in the Park*".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In Topiary Park (formerly Old Deaf School Park) in Columbus, Ohio, sculptor James T.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Mason re-created the painting in topiary form; the installation was completed in 1989.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The 1986 John Hughes film *Ferris Bueller's Day Off* featured the painting during a scene at the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] This work was featured on *100 Great Paintings*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] After some initial studies with composer Rubin Goldmark, Copland traveled to Paris, where he first studied with Isidor Philipp and Paul Vidal, then with noted pedagogue Nadia Boulanger.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He studied three years with Boulanger, whose eclectic approach to music inspired his own broad taste.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Determined upon his return to the U.S. to make his way as a full-time composer, Copland gave lecture-recitals, wrote works on commission and did some teaching and writing.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] But he found that composing orchestral music in a modernist style, which he had adopted while studying abroad, was unprofitable, particularly in light of the Great Depression.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He shifted in the mid-1930s to a more accessible musical style that mirrored the German idea of *Gebrauchsmusik* ("music for use"), music that could serve utilitarian and artistic purposes.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During the Depression years, he traveled extensively to Europe, Africa, and Mexico, formed an important friendship with Mexican composer Carlos Chávez, and began composing his signature works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During the late 1940s, Copland became aware that Stravinsky and other fellow composers had begun to study Arnold Schoenberg's use of twelve-tone (serial) techniques.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] After he had been exposed to the works of French composer Pierre Boulez, he incorporated serial techniques into his *Piano Quartet* (1950), *Piano Fantasy* (1957), *Connotations* for orchestra (1961), and *Inscape* for orchestra (1967).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Unlike Schoenberg, Copland used his tone rows in much the same fashion as his tonal material—as sources for melodies and harmonies, rather than as complete statements in their own right, except for crucial events from a structural point of view.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] From the 1960s onward, Copland's activities turned more from composing to conducting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He became a frequent guest conductor of orchestras in the U.S. and the UK and made a series of recordings of his music, primarily for Columbia Records.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Aaron Copland was born in Brooklyn, New York, on November 14, 1900.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He was the youngest of five children in a Conservative Jewish immigrant family of Lithuanian origin.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While emigrating from Russia to the United States, Copland's father, Harris Morris Copland, lived and worked in Scotland for two to three years to pay for his boat fare to the United States.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] It was there that Copland's father may have Anglicized his surname "Kaplan" to "Copland", though Copland himself believed for many years that the change had been caused by an Ellis Island immigration official when his father entered the country.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland was unaware until late in his life that the family name had been Kaplan, his parents having never told him.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Throughout his childhood, Copland and his family lived above his parents' Brooklyn shop, H.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's, at 628 Washington Avenue (which Aaron later called "a kind of neighborhood Macy's"), on the corner of Dean Street and Washington Avenue, and most of the children helped out in the store.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The family members were active in Congregation Baith Israel Anshei Emes, where Aaron celebrated his bar mitzvah, for which he studied under Israel Goldfarb.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Not especially athletic, the sensitive young man became an avid reader and often read Horatio Alger stories on his front steps.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's father had no musical interest.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His mother, Sarah Mittenthal Copland, sang, played the piano, and arranged music lessons for her children.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland had four older siblings: two brothers, Ralph and Leon, and two sisters, Laurine and Josephine.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Of his siblings, his oldest brother Ralph was the most advanced musically; he was proficient on the violin.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Laurine had the strongest connection with Aaron; she gave him his first piano lessons, promoted his musical education, and supported him in his musical career.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] A student at the Metropolitan Opera School and frequent opera-goer, Laurine also brought home libretti for Aaron to study.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland attended Boys High School and in the summer went to various camps.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Most of his early exposure to music was at Jewish weddings and ceremonies, and occasional family musicales.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland began writing songs at the age of eight and a half.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His earliest notated music, about seven bars he wrote when age 11, was for an opera scenario he created and called *Zenatello*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] From 1913 to 1917 he took piano lessons with Leopold Wolfsohn, who taught him the standard classical fare.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's first public music performance was at a Wanamaker's recital.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] By age 15, after attending a concert by Polish composer-pianist Ignacy Jan Paderewski, Copland decided to become a composer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] At 16, he heard his first symphony, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] After attempts to further his music study from a correspondence course, Copland took formal lessons in harmony, theory, and composition from Rubin Goldmark, a noted teacher and composer of American music (who had given George Gershwin three lessons).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Goldmark, with whom Copland studied between 1917 and 1921, gave the young Copland a solid foundation, especially in the Germanic tradition.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] As Copland later said: "This was a stroke of luck for me.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] I was spared the floundering that so many musicians have suffered through incompetent teaching." But Copland also said that Goldmark had "little sympathy for the advanced musical idioms of the day" and his "approved" composers ended with Richard Strauss.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's graduation piece from his studies with Goldmark was a three-movement piano sonata in a Romantic style.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] But he had also composed more original and daring pieces that he did not share with his teacher.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In addition to regularly attending the Metropolitan Opera and the New York Symphony, where he heard the standard classical repertory, Copland continued his musical development through an expanding circle of musical friends.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] After graduating from high school, he played in dance bands.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Continuing his musical education, he received further piano lessons from Victor Wittgenstein, who found him "quiet, shy, well-mannered, and gracious in accepting criticism".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's fascination with the Russian Revolution and its promise for freeing the lower classes drew a rebuke from his father and uncles.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In spite of that, in his early adult life, Copland developed friendships with people who had socialist and communist leanings.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's passion for the latest European music, plus glowing letters from his friend Aaron Schaffer, inspired him to go to Paris for further study.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] An article in *Musical America* about a summer school program for American musicians at the Fontainebleau School of Music, offered by the French government, encouraged Copland further.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His father wanted him to go to college, but his mother's vote in the family conference allowed him to give Paris a try.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] On arriving in France, he studied at Fontainebleau with pianist and pedagog Isidor Philipp and composer Paul Vidal.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] When Copland found Vidal too much like Goldmark, he switched at the suggestion of a fellow student to Nadia Boulanger, then aged 34.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Boulanger had as many as 40 students at once and employed a formal regimen that Copland had to follow.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland found her incisive mind much to his liking and her ability to critique a composition impeccable.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Boulanger "could always find the weak spot in a place you suspected was weak...
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] She also could tell you *why* it was weak [italics Copland]." He wrote in a letter to his brother Ralph, "This intellectual Amazon is not only professor at the Conservatoire, is not only familiar with all music from Bach to Stravinsky, but is prepared for anything worse in the way of dissonance.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] A more charming womanly woman never lived." Copland later wrote: "it was wonderful for me to find a teacher with such openness of mind, while at the same time she held firm ideas of right and wrong in musical matters.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Along with his studies with Boulanger, Copland took classes in French language and history at the Sorbonne, attended plays, and frequented Shakespeare and Company, the English-language bookstore that was a gathering place for expatriate American writers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Among this group in the heady cultural atmosphere of Paris in the 1920s were Paul Bowles, Ernest Hemingway, Sinclair Lewis, Henry Miller, Gertrude Stein, and Ezra Pound, as well as artists like Pablo Picasso, Marc Chagall, and Amedeo Modigliani.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Also influential on the new music were the French intellectuals Marcel Proust, Paul Valéry, Jean-Paul Sartre, and André Gide; Copland said the latter was his favorite and most read.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Travels to Italy, Austria, and Germany rounded out Copland's musical education.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During his stay in Paris, he began writing musical critiques, the first on Gabriel Fauré, which helped spread his fame and stature in the music community.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland returned to America optimistic and enthusiastic about the future, determined to make his way as a full-time composer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He rented a studio apartment on New York City's Upper West Side in the Empire Hotel, close to Carnegie Hall and other musical venues and publishers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He remained in that area for the next 30 years, later moving to Westchester County, New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland lived frugally and survived financially with help from two $2,500 Guggenheim Fellowships in 1925 and 1926 (each of the two equivalent to $45,897 in 2025).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Lecture-recitals, awards, appointments, and small commissions, plus some teaching, writing, and personal loans, kept him afloat in the subsequent years through World War II.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Also important, especially during the Depression, were wealthy patrons who underwrote performances, helped pay for publication of works, and promoted musical events and composers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Among them was Serge Koussevitzky, the music director of the Boston Symphony Orchestra, who was known as a champion of "new music".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Koussevitsky proved to be very influential in Copland's life, perhaps the second most important figure in Copland's career after Boulanger.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Beginning with the Symphony for Organ and Orchestra (1924), Koussevitzky performed more of Copland's music than that of any the composer's contemporaries, at a time when other conductors were programming only a few of Copland's works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Soon after his return to the United States, Copland was exposed to the artistic circle of photographer Alfred Stieglitz.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Evans's photographs inspired portions of Copland's opera *The Tender Land*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In his quest to take up the slogan of the Stieglitz group, "Affirm America", Copland found only the music of Carl Ruggles and Charles Ives upon which to draw.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Without what Copland called a "usable past" in American classical composers, he looked to jazz and popular music, something he had started to do while in Europe.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In the 1920s, Gershwin, Bessie Smith, and Louis Armstrong were in the forefront of American popular music and jazz.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] By the end of the decade, Copland felt his music was going in a more abstract, less jazz-oriented direction.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] But as large swing bands such as those of Benny Goodman and Glenn Miller became popular in the 1930s, Copland took a renewed interest in the genre.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Inspired by the example of Les Six in France, Copland sought out contemporaries such as Roger Sessions, Roy Harris, Virgil Thomson, and Walter Piston, and quickly established himself as a spokesperson for composers of his generation.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He also helped found the Copland-Sessions Concerts to showcase these composers' chamber works to new audiences.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's relationship with these men, who became known as "commando unit", was one of both support and rivalry, and he played a key role in keeping them together until after World War II.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] With the knowledge he had gained from his studies in Paris, Copland came into demand as a lecturer and writer on contemporary European classical music.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] From 1927 to 1930 and from 1935 to 1938, he taught classes at The New School for Social Research in New York City.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Eventually, his New School lectures appeared in the form of two books—*What to Listen for in Music* (1937, revised 1957) and *Our New Music* (1940, revised 1968 and retitled *The New Music: 1900–1960*).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During this period, Copland also wrote regularly for *The New York Times*, *The Musical Quarterly*, and other journals.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] These articles appeared in 1960 as the book *Copland on Music*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During his time at The New School, Copland was active as a presenter and curator, using The New School to present a wide range of composers and artists.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's compositions in the early 1920s reflected the modernist attitude that prevailed among intellectuals, that the arts need be accessible to only a cadre of the enlightened, and that the masses would come to appreciate their efforts over time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] But mounting troubles with the *Symphonic Ode* (1929) and *Short Symphony* (1933) caused Copland to rethink this approach.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] It was financially unprofitable, particularly during the Depression.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Avant-garde music had lost what cultural historian Morris Dickstein calls "its buoyant experimental edge" and the national attitude toward it had changed.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In many ways, this shift mirrored the German idea of *Gebrauchsmusik* ("music for use"), as composers sought to create music that could serve a utilitarian as well as artistic purpose.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This approach encompassed two trends: first, music that students could easily learn, and second, music which would have wider appeal, such as incidental music for plays, movies, radio, etc.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] To this end, Copland provided musical advice and inspiration to The Group Theatre, a company that also attracted Stella Adler, Elia Kazan, and Lee Strasberg.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Philosophically an outgrowth of Stieglitz and his ideals, the Group focused on socially relevant plays by American authors.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Through it and later his work in film, Copland met several major American playwrights, including Thornton Wilder, William Inge, Arthur Miller, and Edward Albee, and considered projects with all of them.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Around 1935 Copland began to compose musical pieces for young audiences, in accordance with the first goal of American Gebrauchsmusik.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] These works included piano pieces (*The Young Pioneers*) and an opera (*The Second Hurricane*).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During the Depression years, Copland traveled extensively to Europe, Africa, and Mexico.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He formed an important friendship with Mexican composer Carlos Chávez and returned often to Mexico for working vacations conducting engagements.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During his initial visit to Mexico, Copland began composing the first of his signature works, *El Salón México*, completed in 1936.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In it and in *The Second Hurricane* Copland began "experimenting", as he phrased it, with a simpler, more accessible style.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This and other incidental commissions fulfilled the second goal of American Gebrauchsmusik, creating music of wide appeal.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Concurrent with *The Second Hurricane*, Copland composed (for radio broadcast) "Prairie Journal" on a commission from the Columbia Broadcast System.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This was one of his first pieces to convey the landscape of the American West.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This emphasis on the frontier carried over to his ballet *Billy the Kid* (1938), which along with *El Salón México* became his first widespread public success.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's ballet music established him as an authentic composer of American music much as Stravinsky's ballet scores connected the composer with Russian music and came at an opportune time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He helped fill a vacuum for American choreographers to fill their dance repertory and tapped into an artistic groundswell, from the motion pictures of Busby Berkeley and Fred Astaire to the ballets of George Balanchine and Martha Graham, to both democratize and Americanize dance as an art form.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1938, Copland helped form the American Composers Alliance to promote and publish American contemporary classical music.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He was president of the organization from 1939 to 1945.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1939, Copland completed his first two Hollywood film scores, for *Of Mice and Men* and *Our Town*, and composed the radio score "John Henry", based on the folk ballad.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While these works and others like them that followed were accepted by the listening public at large, detractors accused Copland of pandering to the masses.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Music critic Paul Rosenfeld, for one, warned in 1939 that Copland was "standing in the fork in the high road, the two branches of which lead respectively to popular and artistic success".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Even some of Copland's friends, such as composer Arthur Berger, were confused about Copland's simpler style.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The 1940s were arguably Copland's most productive years, and some of his works from this period cemented his fame.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His ballet scores for *Rodeo* (1942) and *Appalachian Spring* (1944) were huge successes.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] *Lincoln Portrait* and *Fanfare for the Common Man* became patriotic standards.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Composed from 1944 to 1946, it became Copland's best-known symphony.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The Clarinet Concerto (1948), scored for solo clarinet, strings, harp, and piano, was a commission piece for band-leader and clarinetist Benny Goodman and a complement to Copland's earlier jazz-influenced work, the Piano Concerto (1926).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His *Four Piano Blues* is an introspective composition with a jazz influence.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland finished the 1940s with two film scores, one for William Wyler's *The Heiress* and one for the film adaptation of John Steinbeck's novel *The Red Pony*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1949, Copland returned to Europe, where he found French composer Pierre Boulez dominating the group of postwar avant-garde composers there.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He also met with proponents of twelve-tone technique, based on the works of Arnold Schoenberg, and found himself interested in adapting serial methods to his own musical voice.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1950, Copland received a U.S.-Italy Fulbright Commission scholarship to study in Rome, which he did the following year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Around this time, he also composed his Piano Quartet, adopting Schoenberg's twelve-tone method, and *Old American Songs* (1950), the first set of which was premiered by Peter Pears and Benjamin Britten, the second by William Warfield.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During the 1951–52 academic year, Copland gave a series of lectures under the Charles Eliot Norton Professorship at Harvard University.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] These lectures were published as the book *Music and Imagination*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Because of his leftist views, which had included his support of the Communist Party USA ticket during the 1936 presidential election and his strong support of Progressive Party candidate Henry A.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Wallace in the 1948 presidential election, Copland was investigated by the FBI during the Red scare of the 1950s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He was included on an FBI list of 151 artists thought to have Communist associations and found himself blacklisted, with *A Lincoln Portrait* withdrawn from the 1953 inaugural concert for President Dwight Eisenhower.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Called later that year to a private hearing at the United States Capitol in Washington, D.C., Copland was questioned by Joseph McCarthy and Roy Cohn about his lecturing abroad and his affiliations with various organizations and events.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] McCarthy and Cohn ignored Copland's works, which made a virtue of American values.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Outraged by the accusations, many members of the musical community held up Copland's music as a banner of his patriotism.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The investigations ceased in 1955 and were closed in 1975.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The McCarthy probes did not seriously affect Copland's career and international artistic reputation, however taxing as they might have been on his time, energy, and emotional state.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Nevertheless, beginning in 1950, Copland—who had been appalled at Stalin's persecution of Dmitri Shostakovich and other artists—began resigning from participation in leftist groups.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland, Pollack writes, "stayed particularly concerned about the role of the artist in society".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He decried the lack of artistic freedom in the Soviet Union, and in his 1954 Norton lecture he asserted that loss of freedom under Soviet Communism deprived artists of "the immemorial right of the artist to be wrong." He began to vote Democratic, first for Stevenson and then for Kennedy.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Potentially more damaging for Copland was a sea change in artistic tastes, away from the Populist mores that infused his work of the 1930s and 40s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Beginning in the 1940s, intellectuals assailed Popular Front culture, to which Copland's music was linked, and labeled it, in Dickstein's words, "hopelessly middlebrow, a dumbing down of art into toothless entertainment".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] They often linked their disdain for Populist art with technology, new media and mass audiences—in other words, the areas of radio, television and motion pictures, for which Copland either had or soon would write music, as well as his popular ballets.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While these attacks actually began at the end of the 1930s with the writings of Clement Greenberg and Dwight Macdonald for *Partisan Review*, they were based in anti-Stalinist politics and accelerated in the decades following World War II.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In Japan, he was taken with the work of Tōru Takemitsu and began a correspondence with him that lasted over the next decade.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland revised his text "The New Music" with comments on the styles that he encountered.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He found much of what he heard dull and impersonal.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Electronic music seemed to have "a depressing sameness of sound", while aleatoric music was for those "who enjoy teetering on the edge of chaos".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] As he summarized, "I've spent most of my life trying to get the right note in the right place.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1952, Copland received a commission from the League of Composers, funded by a grant from Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein, to write an opera for television.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While Copland was aware of the potential pitfalls of that genre, which included weak libretti and demanding production values, he had also been thinking about writing an opera since the 1940s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The resulting opera, *The Tender Land*, was written in two acts but later expanded to three.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] As Copland feared, when the opera premiered in 1954 critics found the libretto to be weak.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In spite of its flaws, the opera became one of the few American operas to enter the standard repertory.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1957, 1958, and 1976, Copland was the music director of the Ojai Music Festival, a classical and contemporary music festival in Ojai, California.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] For the occasion of the Metropolitan Museum of Art Centennial, Copland composed *Ceremonial Fanfare for Brass Ensemble* to accompany the exhibition "Masterpieces of Fifty Centuries." Leonard Bernstein, Piston, William Schuman, and Thomson also composed pieces for the museum's Centennial exhibitions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] From the 1960s onward, Copland turned increasingly to conducting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In 1960, RCA Victor released Copland's recordings with the Boston Symphony Orchestra of the orchestral suites from *Appalachian Spring* and *The Tender Land*; these recordings were later reissued on CD, as were most of Copland's Columbia recordings (by Sony).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] From 1960 until his death, Copland resided at Cortlandt Manor, New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Known as Rock Hill, his home was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 2003 and further designated a National Historic Landmark in 2008.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's health deteriorated through the 1980s, and he died of Alzheimer's disease and respiratory failure on December 2, 1990, in North Tarrytown, New York (now Sleepy Hollow).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Following his death, his ashes were scattered over the Tanglewood Music Center near Lenox, Massachusetts.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Much of his large estate was bequeathed to the creation of the Aaron Copland Fund for Composers, which bestows over $600,000 per year to performing groups.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland never enrolled as a member of any political party.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Nevertheless, he inherited a considerable interest in civic and world events from his father.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His views were generally progressive and he had strong ties with numerous colleagues and friends in the Popular Front, including Clifford Odets.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He condemned it as "almost worse for art than the real thing".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Throw the artist "into a mood of suspicion, ill-will, and dread that typifies the cold war attitude and he'll create nothing".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While Copland had various encounters with organized religious thought, which influenced some of his early compositions, he remained agnostic.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He was close with Zionism during the Popular Front movement, when it was endorsed by the left.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Pollack states that Copland was gay and that the composer came to an early acceptance and understanding of his sexuality.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Like many at that time, Copland guarded his privacy, especially in regard to his homosexuality.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He provided few written details about his private life, and even after the Stonewall riots of 1969, showed no inclination to "come out".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] However, he was one of the few composers of his stature to live openly and travel with his intimates.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] They tended to be talented, younger men involved in the arts, and the age-gap between them and the composer widened as he grew older.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Most became enduring friends after a few years and, in Pollack's words, "remained a primary source of companionship".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Among Copland's love affairs were ones with photographer Victor Kraft, artist Alvin Ross, pianist Paul Moor, dancer Erik Johns, composer John Brodbin Kennedy, and painter Prentiss Taylor.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Victor Kraft became a constant in Copland's life, though their romance might have ended by 1944.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Originally a violin prodigy when the composer met him in 1932, Kraft gave up music to pursue a career in photography, in part due to Copland's urging.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Kraft would leave and re-enter Copland's life, often bringing much stress with him as his behavior became increasingly erratic, sometimes confrontational.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Kraft fathered a child to whom Copland later provided financial security, through a bequest from his estate.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Vivian Perlis, who collaborated with Copland on his autobiography, writes: "Copland's method of composing was to write down fragments of musical ideas as they came to him.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] When he needed a piece, he would turn to these ideas (his 'gold nuggets')." If one or more of these nuggets looked promising, he would then write a piano sketch and eventually work on them at the keyboard.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The piano, Perlis writes, "was so integral to his composing that it permeated his compositional style, not only in the frequent use in the instrument but in more subtle and complex ways".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His habit of turning to the keyboard tended to embarrass Copland until he learned that Stravinsky also did so.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland would not consider the specific instrumentation for a piece until it was complete and notated.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Nor, according to Pollack, did he generally work in linear fashion, from beginning to end of a composition.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Instead, he tended to compose whole sections in no particular order and surmise their eventual sequence after all those parts were complete, much like assembling a collage.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland himself admitted, "I don't compose.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] I assemble materials." Many times, he included material he had written years earlier.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] If the situation dictated, as it did with his film scores, Copland could work quickly.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Otherwise, he tended to write slowly whenever possible.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Even with this deliberation, Copland considered composition, in his words, "the product of the emotions", which included "self-expression" and "self-discovery".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While Copland's earliest musical inclinations as a teenager ran toward Chopin, Debussy, Verdi and the Russian composers, Copland's teacher and mentor Nadia Boulanger became his most important influence.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland especially admired Boulanger's total grasp of all classical music, and he was encouraged to experiment and develop a "clarity of conception and elegance in proportion".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Following her model, he studied all periods of classical music and all forms—from madrigals to symphonies.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This breadth of vision led Copland to compose music for numerous settings—orchestra, opera, solo piano, small ensemble, art song, ballet, theater and film.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Boulanger particularly emphasized "la grande ligne" (the long line), "a sense of forward motion ... the feeling for inevitability, for the creating of an entire piece that could be thought of as a functioning entity".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During his studies with Boulanger in Paris, Copland was excited to be so close to the new post-Impressionistic French music of Ravel, Roussel, and Satie, as well as Les Six, a group that included Milhaud, Poulenc, and Honegger.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Webern, Berg, and Bartók also impressed him.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland was "insatiable" in seeking out the newest European music, whether in concerts, score reading or heated debate.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] These "moderns" were discarding the old laws of composition and experimenting with new forms, harmonies and rhythms, and including the use of jazz and quarter-tone music.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Milhaud was Copland's inspiration for some of his earlier "jazzy" works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He was also exposed to Schoenberg and admired his earlier atonal pieces, thinking Schoenberg's *Pierrot lunaire* above all others.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland named Igor Stravinsky as his "hero" and his favorite 20th-century composer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland especially admired Stravinsky's "jagged and uncouth rhythmic effects", "bold use of dissonance", and "hard, dry, crackling sonority".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Another inspiration for much of Copland's music was jazz.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Beginning in 1923, he employed "jazzy elements" in his classical music, but by the late 1930s, he moved on to Latin and American folk tunes in his more successful pieces.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Although his early focus of jazz gave way to other influences, Copland continued to make use of jazz in more subtle ways in later works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's work from the late 1940s onward included experimentation with Schoenberg's twelve-tone system, resulting in two major works, the Piano Quartet (1950) and the Piano Fantasy (1957).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's compositions before leaving for Paris were mainly short works for piano and art songs, inspired by Liszt and Debussy.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In them, he experimented with ambiguous beginnings and endings, rapid key changes, and the frequent use of tritones.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] His first published work, *The Cat and the Mouse* (1920), was a piece for piano solo based on the Jean de La Fontaine fable "The Old Cat and the Young Mouse".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In *Three Moods* (1921), Copland's final movement is entitled "Jazzy", which he noted "is based on two jazz melodies and ought to make the old professors sit up and take notice".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The Symphony for Organ and Orchestra established Copland as a serious modern composer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Murchinson points out the influence of Igor Stravinsky in the work's nervous, driving rhythms and some of its harmonic language.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland in hindsight found the work too "European" as he sought a more consciously American idiom to evoke in his future work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Visits to Europe in 1926 and 1927 brought him into contact with the most recent developments there, including Webern's Five Pieces for Orchestra, which greatly impressed him.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In August 1927, while staying in Königstein, Copland wrote *Poet's Song*, a setting of a text by E.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Cummings and his first composition using Schoenberg's twelve-tone technique.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This was followed by the *Symphonic Ode* (1929) and the Piano Variations (1930), both of which rely on the exhaustive development of a single short motif.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The other major work of Copland's first period is the *Short Symphony* (1933).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In it, music critic and musicologist Michael Steinberg writes, the "jazz-influenced dislocations of meter that are so characteristic of Copland's music of the 1920s are more prevalent than ever".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Compared to the *Symphonic Ode*, the orchestration is much leaner and the composition itself more concentrated.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In its combination and refinement of modernist and jazz elements, Steinberg calls the *Short Symphony* "a remarkable synthesis of the learned and the vernacular, and thus, in all its brevity [the work last just 15 minutes], a singularly 'complete' representation of its composer".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] However, Copland moved from this work toward more accessible works and folk sources.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland wrote *El Salón México* between 1932 and 1936, which met with a popular acclaim that contrasted the relative obscurity of most of his previous works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Inspiration for this work came from Copland's vivid recollection of visiting the "Salon Mexico" dancehall where he witnessed a more intimate view of Mexico's nightlife.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland derived his melodic material for this piece freely from two collections of Mexican folk tunes, changing pitches and varying rhythms.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The use of a folk tune with variations set in a symphonic context started a pattern he repeated in many of his most successful works right on through the 1940s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] It also marked a shift in emphasis from a unified musical structure to the rhetorical effect the music might have on an audience and showed Copland refining a simplified, more accessible musical language.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's brand of nationalism in his ballets differed from that of European composers such as Béla Bartók, who tried to preserve the folk tones they used as close to the original as possible.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland enhanced the tunes he used with contemporary rhythms, textures and structures.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In what could seem contradictory, he used complex harmonies and rhythms to simplify folk melodies and make them more accessible and familiar to his listeners.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Except for the Shaker tune in *Appalachian Spring*, Copland often syncopates traditional melodies, changes their metric patterns and note values.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In *Billy the Kid*, he derives many of the work's sparse harmonies from the implied harmonic constructions of the cowboy tunes themselves.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Like Stravinsky, Copland mastered the ability to create a coherent, integrated composition from what was essentially a mosaic of divergent folk-based and original elements.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In that sense, Copland's Populist works such as *Billy the Kid*, *Rodeo*, *Appalachian Spring* are not far removed from Stravinsky's ballet *The Rite of Spring*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Within that framework, however, Copland preserved the American atmosphere of these ballets through what musicologist Elliott Antokoletz calls "the conservative handling of open diatonic sonorities", which fosters "a pastoral quality" in the music.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This is especially true in the opening of *Appalachian Spring*, where the harmonizations remain "transparent and bare, suggested by the melodic disposition of the Shaker tune".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Variations which contrast to this tune in rhythm, key, texture and dynamics, fit within Copland's compositional practice of juxtaposing structural blocks.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] When Hollywood beckoned concert hall composers in the 1930s with promises of better films and higher pay, Copland saw both a challenge for his abilities as a composer as well as an opportunity to expand his reputation and audience for his more serious works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] In a departure from other film scores of the time, Copland's work largely reflected his own style, instead of the usual borrowing from the late-Romantic period.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He often avoided the full orchestra, and he rejected the common practice of using a leitmotif to identify characters with their own personal themes.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He instead matched a theme to the action, while avoiding the underlining of every action with exaggerated emphasis.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Another technique Copland employed was to keep silent during intimate screen moments and only begin the music as a confirming motive toward the end of a scene.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Virgil Thomson wrote that the score for *Of Mice and Men* established "the most distinguished populist musical style yet created in America".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Many composers who scored for Western movies, particularly between 1940 and 1960, were influenced by Copland's style, though some also followed the late Romantic "Max Steiner" approach, which was considered more conventional and desirable.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's work in the late 1940s and 1950s included use of Schoenberg's twelve-tone system, a development that he had recognized but not fully embraced.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He had also believed the atonality of serialized music to run counter to his desire to reach a wide audience.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland therefore approached dodecaphony with some initial skepticism.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] While in Europe in 1949, he heard a number of serial works but did not admire much of it because "so often it seemed that individuality was sacrificed to the method".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The music of French composer Pierre Boulez showed Copland that the technique could be separated from the "old Wagnerian" aesthetic with which he had associated it previously.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Subsequent exposure to the late music of Austrian composer Anton Webern and twelve-tone pieces by Swiss composer Frank Martin and Italian composer Luigi Dallapiccola strengthened this opinion.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland came to the conclusion that composing along serial lines was "nothing more than an angle of vision.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Like fugal treatment, it is a stimulus that enlivens musical thinking, especially when applied to a series of tones that lend themselves to that treatment." He began his first serial work, the "Piano Fantasy", in 1951 to fulfill a commission from the young virtuoso pianist William Kapell.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The piece became one of his most challenging works, over which he labored until 1957.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] During the work's development, in 1953, Kapell died in an aircraft crash.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Critics lauded the "Fantasy" when it was finally premiered, calling the piece "an outstanding addition to his own oeuvre and to contemporary piano literature" and "a tremendous achievement".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Serialism allowed Copland a synthesis of serial and non-serial practices.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Before he did this, according to musicologist Joseph Straus, the philosophical and compositional difference between non-tonal composers such as Schoenberg and tonal composers like Stravinsky had been considered too wide a gulf to bridge.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland wrote that, to him, serialism pointed in two opposite directions, one "toward the extreme of total organization with electronic applications" and the other "a gradual absorption into what had become a very *freely interpreted tonalism* [italics Copland]".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] The path he said he chose was the latter one, which he said, when he described his *Piano Fantasy*, allowed him to incorporate "elements able to be associated with the twelve-tone method and also with music tonally conceived".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] This practice differed markedly from Schoenberg, who used his tone rows as complete statements around which to structure his compositions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Copland used his rows not very differently from how he fashioned the material in his tonal pieces.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] He saw his rows as sources for melodies and harmonies, not as complete and independent entities, except at points in the musical structure that dictated the complete statement of a row.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p01] Even after Copland started using 12-tone techniques, he did not stick to them exclusively but went back and forth between tonal and non-tonal compositions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland did not consider himself a professional writer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] He called his writing "a byproduct of my trade" as "a kind of salesman for contemporary music".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] As such, he wrote prolifically about music, including pieces on music criticism analysis, on musical trends, and on his own compositions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] An avid lecturer and lecturer-performer, Copland eventually collected his presentation notes into three books, *What to Listen for in Music* (1939), *Our New Music* (1941), and *Music and Imagination* (1952).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] In the 1980s, he collaborated with Vivian Perlis on a two-volume autobiography, *Copland: 1900 Through 1942* (1984) and *Copland Since 1943* (1989).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Along with the composer's first-person narrative, these two books incorporate 11 "interludes" by Perlis and other sections from friends and peers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Some controversy arose over the second volume's increased reliance over the first on old documents for source material.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Due to the then-advanced stage of Copland's Alzheimer's and the resulting memory loss, however, this fallback to previous material was inevitable.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] The use in both books of letters and other unpublished sources, expertly researched and organized, made them what Pollack terms "invaluable".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] During his career, Copland met and helped hundreds of young composers, whom he met and who were drawn to him by his continual interest and acuity into the contemporary musical scene.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland's willingness to foster talent extended to critiquing scores in progress that were presented to him by his peers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Composer William Schuman writes: "As a teacher, Aaron was extraordinary....
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland would look at your music and try to understand what *you* were after [italics Schuman].
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] He didn't want to turn you into another Aaron Copland....
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] When he questioned something, it was in a manner that might make you want to question it yourself.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Everything he said was helpful in making a younger composer realize the potential of a particular work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Although Copland studied conducting in Paris in 1921, he remained essentially a self-taught conductor with a very personal style.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Encouraged by Igor Stravinsky to master conducting and perhaps emboldened by Carlos Chavez's efforts in Mexico, he began to direct his own works on his international travels in the 1940s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] By the 1950s, he was also conducting the works of other composers, and after a televised appearance where he directed the New York Philharmonic, Copland became in high demand.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] He placed a strong emphasis in his programs on 20th-century music and lesser-known composers, and until the 1970s rarely planned concerts to feature his music exclusively.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Performers and audiences generally greeted his conducting appearances as positive opportunities to hear his music as the composer intended.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] His efforts on behalf of other composers could be penetrating but also uneven.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Understated on the podium, Copland modeled his style after other composer/conductors such as Stravinsky and Paul Hindemith.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Critics wrote of his precision and clarity before an orchestra.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Observers noted that he had "none of the typical conductorial vanities".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland's unpretentious charm was appreciated by professional musicians but some criticized his "unsteady" beat and "unexciting" interpretations.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Koussevitzky advised him to "stay home and compose".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland at times asked for conducting advice from Bernstein, who occasionally joked that Copland could conduct his works "a little better".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Bernstein also noted that Copland improved over time, and he considered him a more natural conductor than Stravinsky or Hindemith.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Eventually, Copland recorded nearly all his orchestral works with himself conducting.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland wrote a total of about 100 works which covered a diverse range of genres.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Many of these compositions, especially orchestral pieces, have remained part of the standard American repertoire.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] The composer himself pointed out, in summarizing the American character of his music, "the optimistic tone", "his love of rather large canvases", "a certain directness in expression of sentiment", and "a certain songfulness".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] While "Copland's musical rhetoric has become iconic" and "has functioned as a mirror of America", conductor Leon Botstein suggests that the composer "helped define the modern consciousness of America's ideals, character and sense of place.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] The notion that his music played not a subsidiary but a central role in the shaping of the national consciousness makes Copland uniquely interesting, for the historian as well as the musician." Composer Ned Rorem states, "Aaron stressed simplicity: Remove, remove, remove what isn't needed....
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Aaron brought leanness to America, which set the tone for our musical language throughout [World War II].
[src:alfred-stieglitz/aaron-copland-p02] Copland's music was prominently featured throughout Spike Lee's 1998 film, *He Got Game*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Born in Paris in 1889, Abel Gance was the illegitimate son of a prosperous doctor, Abel Flamant, and a working-class mother, Françoise Péréthon (or Perthon).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Initially taking his mother's name, he was brought up until the age of eight by his maternal grandparents in the coal-mining town of Commentry in central France.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He then returned to Paris to rejoin his mother, who had by then married Adolphe Gance, a chauffeur and mechanic, whose name Abel then adopted.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Although he later fabricated the history of a brilliant school career and middle-class background, Gance left school at the age of 14, and the love of literature and art which sustained him throughout his life was in part the result of self-education.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He started working as a clerk in a solicitor's office, but after a couple of years he turned to acting in the theatre.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] When he was 18, he was given a season's contract at the Royal Park Theatre in Brussels, where he developed friendships with the actor Victor Francen and the writer Blaise Cendrars.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] While in Brussels, Gance wrote his first film scenarios, which he sold to Léonce Perret.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Back in Paris in 1909, he acted in his first film, Perret's *Molière*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] At that stage, he regarded the cinema as "infantile and stupid" and was only drawn into film jobs by his poverty, but he nevertheless continued to write scenarios, and often sold them to Gaumont.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] During this period he was diagnosed with tuberculosis, often fatal at that time, but after a period of retreat in Vittel he recovered.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] With some friends, he established a production company, Le Film Français, and began directing his own films in 1911 with *La Digue (ou Pour sauver la Hollande)*, a historical film which featured the first screen appearance of Pierre Renoir.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance tried to maintain a connection with the theatre and he finished writing a monumental tragedy entitled *Victoire de Samothrace*, in which he hoped that Sarah Bernhardt would star.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Its five-hour length, and Gance's refusal to cut it, proved to be a stumbling block.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] With the outbreak of World War I, Gance was rejected by the army on medical grounds, and in 1915 he started writing and directing for a new film company, Le Film d'art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He soon caused controversy with *La Folie du docteur Tube*, a comic fantasy in which he and his cameraman Léonce-Henri Burel created some arresting visual effects with distorting mirrors.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The producers were outraged and refused to show the film.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance nevertheless continued working for Film d'Art until 1918, making over a dozen commercially successful films.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] His experiments included tracking shots, extreme close-ups, low-angle shots, and split-screen images.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] His subjects moved steadily away from simple action films towards psychological melodramas, such as *Mater dolorosa* (1917) starring Emmy Lynn as a neglected wife who has an affair with her husband's brother.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The film was a great commercial success, and it was followed by *La Dixième Symphonie*, another marital drama featuring Emmy Lynn.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Here Gance's mastery of lighting, composition and editing was accompanied by a range of literary and artistic references which some critics found pretentious and alienating.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] In 1917, Gance was finally drafted into the army, in its Service Cinématographique, an episode which proved futile and short-lived, but it deepened his preoccupation with the impact of the war and the depression which was caused by the deaths of many of his friends.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] When he parted company with Film d'Art over a shortage of funds, Charles Pathé stepped in to underwrite his next film, *J'accuse* (1919), in which Gance confronted the waste and suffering which the war had brought.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He re-enlisted in the Service Cinématographique in order to be able to film some scenes on a real battlefield at the front.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The film made a powerful impact and went on to have international distribution.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Nevertheless, Gance brought an unprecedented level of energy and imagination to the technical realisation of his story, set firstly against the dark and grimy background of locomotives and railway yards, and then among the snow-covered landscapes of the Alps.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He employed elaborate editing techniques and innovative use of rapid cutting which made the film highly influential among other contemporary directors.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The finished film was originally in 32 reels and ran for nearly nine hours, but it was subsequently edited down for distribution.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] A modern reconstruction from five different versions, available on DVD, is nearly four and a half hours long, and an almost seven hours long restored version was shown at the 2019 Lumière Film Festival.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] In 1921, Gance visited America to promote *J'accuse*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He was also offered a contract with MGM to work in Hollywood, but he turned it down.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] After a brief change of pace for *Au Secours!* (1924), a comic film with Max Linder, Gance embarked on his greatest project, a six-part life of *Napoléon*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Only the first part was completed, tracing Bonaparte's early life, through the Revolution, and up to the invasion of Italy, but even this occupied a vast canvas with meticulously recreated historical scenes and scores of characters.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The original version of the film ran for around 6 hours.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] A shortened version received a triumphant première at the Paris Opéra in April 1927 before a distinguished audience that included the future General de Gaulle.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The length was reduced still further for French and European distribution, and it became even shorter when it was shown in America.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] This was not the end of the film's career however.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance re-used material from it in later films, and the restoration of the silent film at the beginning of the 1980s confirmed it as his best known work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance embraced the arrival of sound with enthusiasm, and his first production was *La Fin du monde* (1931), an expensive science-fiction film (first planned in 1913/14) about the imminent collision of a comet with the Earth.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The film was a critical and commercial disaster, and thereafter the creative independence which Gance had enjoyed in the previous decade was seriously curtailed.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance continued to be a busy film-maker throughout the 1930s, but he characterised most of the films made during this period as ones that he did "not in order to live, but in order not to die".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] In 1932 he tried to demonstrate his credentials as a reliable and efficient director by filming a remake of *Mater dolorosa* which he completed within 18 days and within budget.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Among the other 'commercial' works that followed were *Lucrezia Borgia* (1935), with Edwige Feuillère, and *Un Grand Amour de Beethoven* (1937), with Harry Baur.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] One of the more personal projects that he was able to undertake was a new version of *J'accuse!* (1938), not so much a remake of his 1919 film as a continuation of it, and conceived as a warning against the new war that he saw impending.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] His next film *Paradis perdu*, a melodrama about the First World War, proved successful when it was released after the Fall of France in 1940.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance then filmed a popular melodrama called *Vénus aveugle*, which he saw as an allegory of the current state of France and a message of hope directed to the ordinary French people in their time of misfortune.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] That year, Gance was denounced as a Jew, and was trying to get his name removed from the list of non-aryens forbidden to practice their profession.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] At the feat of pursuing his work, Gance complied with the Vichy government and was among those who saw Philippe Pétain as the means of the country's salvation.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] In September 1941 *Vénus aveugle* had its first screening in Vichy, preceded by a speech in which Gance paid tribute to Pétain.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] After completing one more film, *Le Capitaine Fracasse*, Gance eventually fled to Spain in August 1943, citing growing hostility from the German authorities in France, and he remained there until October 1945.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] In the post-World War II era, his difficulties in getting support for his projects increased, and thus he made few films.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The historical melodrama *La Tour de Nesle* (1954) was his first film in colour, and it provoked some revival of interest in his work, with critics such as François Truffaut making the case for Gance as a neglected *auteur* of genius.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance returned to Napoleonic spectacle with *Austerlitz* (1960), and made a further historical pageant in *Cyrano et d'Artagnan* (1963), before moving into television for his final works, also on historical subjects.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Throughout his life Gance kept returning to *Napoléon*, often editing his own footage into shorter versions, adding a soundtrack, sometimes filming new material, and as a result the original 1927 film was lost from view for decades.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] After various attempts at reconstruction, the dedicated work of the film historian Kevin Brownlow produced a five-hour version of the film, still incomplete but fuller than anyone had seen since the 1920s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] This version was presented at the Telluride Film Festival in August 1979, with the frail 89-year-old director in attendance.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] The occasion brought a belated triumph to Gance's career, and subsequent performances and further restoration made his name known to a worldwide audience.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Abel Gance married three times: in 1912 to Mathilde Thizeau; in 1922 to Marguerite Danis (sister of Ida); and in 1933 to Marie-Odette Vérité (Sylvie Grenade), who died in 1978.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance died of tuberculosis in Paris in 1981 at the age of 92.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Abel Gance was interred in the Cimetière d'Auteuil in Paris.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Gance wanted himself to be seen as "the Victor Hugo of the screen", and many assessments have recognised the ambition, the ingenuity and the sweeping romanticism of his films.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Some, such as Léon Moussinac in the 1920s, have pointed to the contradictions in his work between creativity and cliché, the "abundance of original treasures and of banal mediocrity and of poor taste".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] One thing that has always been acknowledged is Gance's innovations in the techniques of the cinema.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] As well as his multiscreen ventures with Polyvision, he explored the use of superimposition of images, extreme close-ups, and fast rhythmic editing, and he made the camera mobile in unorthodox ways – hand-held, mounted on wires or a pendulum, or even strapped to a horse.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He also made early experiments with the addition of sound to film, and with filming in colour and in 3-D.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] There were few aspects of film technique that he did not seek to incorporate in his work, and his influence was acknowledged by contemporaries such as Jean Epstein and later by the French New Wave film-makers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] In the assessment of Kevin Brownlow, "...with his silent productions, *J'accuse*, *La Roue*, and *Napoléon*, [Abel Gance] made a fuller use of the medium than anyone before or since".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Another aspect of Gance's work which has drawn comment from critics is the political stance and implication of his life and films, particularly his identification with strong military leaders.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Whereas *J'accuse* in 1919 suggested Gance's pacifist and anti-establishment attitude, the reactions to *Napoléon* in 1927 saw greater ambivalence, and some commentators even judged it to be an apologia for dictatorship.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] This strand of criticism of Gance's reactionary politics has continued through later assessments of him; it has also noted his ardent support for Pétain in the early years of World War II, and subsequently for Charles de Gaulle in the 1960s.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Others have regarded these political interpretations as secondary to Gance's mastery of exuberant spectacle, which frequently had a nationalistic focus.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] As one obituary concluded, "Abel Gance was perhaps the greatest Romantic of the screen".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] Abel Gance was a member of the jury for Miss France 1938.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abel-gance] He was also a member of the jury for the 1953 Cannes Film Festival, with Jean Cocteau as president.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú means "chokecherry point" in the Tewa language.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] It is also called Santo Tomás de Abiquiú and the Pueblo of Santo Tomás de Abiquiú.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In the mid-eighteenth century, the Spanish crown provided land grants to *genízaros* here and in other places to establish buffer towns to defend the frontier from raiding tribes such as the Comanche.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú was one of the homes of American artist Georgia O'Keeffe from 1929 until 1984.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The Georgia O'Keeffe Home and Studio is in Abiquiú.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The artist also owned property at the nearby Ghost Ranch.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Many of her paintings depict scenes near Abiquiú.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú was first settled in 1742 by 24 Tewa Pueblo families led by a Roman Catholic priest, Francisco Delgado.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The Tewa returned to New Mexico after a lengthy residence among the Hopi people in what would become Arizona.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Their settlement in Abiquiú was part of the strategy by New Mexican colonists to defend its frontiers against marauding indigenous peoples such as the Apache, Comanche, and Navajo.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú was on the northern border of the Spanish settlements of New Mexico.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In 1747, in one of the numerous raids in the area, the Comanche took 23 women and children captive, forcing the temporary abandonment of Abiquiú.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The captives probably were sold or traded in the flourishing slave trade between and among the Spanish and the surrounding indigenous nations.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In 1754, to deal with the raids and the faltering settlement, New Mexico governor Tomás Vélez Cachupín gave 34 genízaro families a land grant in exchange for them taking a prominent role in frontier defense.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú was the third such genízaro settlement established in New Mexico, after Belen and Trampas.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The genízaros were detribalized Native Americans from various tribes whose origin was typically as war captives, either captured by the Spanish or sold by raiding tribes to the Spanish to work as slaves and servants.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Because they had few rights under the casta laws of the Spanish, acceptance of land grants and resettlement on the dangerous frontier of New Mexico was the principal way for genízaros to become landowners.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú became the archetypal genízaro settlement.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Many residents still celebrate their genízaro heritage in the 21st century.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In the late 18th century, peace was established between New Mexico and the Comanche and the Ute.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] An annual trade fair at Abiquiú drew many indigenous people to the town, especially the Utes, who traded deer skins for horses and tools.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Also, settlers purchased or redeemed captive children from the native people.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Bands of Utes often camped for the winter near Abiquiú.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In the 1840s, the peace with the Utes broke down and 1,000 of them came to Abiquiú with a list of grievances and demands.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Several Utes were killed in this confrontation.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Peace with the Utes was restored in 1849 by the U.S. government, which had recently invaded and conquered New Mexico in the Mexican–American War.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Throughout the 19th century, the residents of Abiquiú struggled to retain ownership of the 16,000 acres (6,500 ha) of land granted them in 1754.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In 1894, their right to the land was validated in the United States Court of Private Land Claims.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] In 1969, additional land, previously designated as National Forest, was returned to the community.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú is a popular tourist destination, and some Anglo-Americans have settled in the community.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Abiquiú was the starting point of the pioneering route of the Old Spanish Trail.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] This first route, the Armijo Route, was led by Antonio Armijo of Santa Fe, with 60 mounted men and a caravan of pack animals carrying blankets and other trade goods to barter for mules in Alta California.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Armijo's caravan left Abiquiú on November 7, 1829, and made the journey to San Gabriel Mission in 86 days, arriving on January 31, 1830.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] He returned by the same route in 56 days, leaving on March 1 and arriving on April 25, 1830.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] Armijo documented his route daily, unlike travelers on other routes of the Old Spanish Trail.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] These reports were very brief, listing dates and stopping places with few other details and no distances recorded.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] He submitted them to the governor, José Antonio Chaves, and the Mexican government published them on June 19, 1830.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The climate of Abiquiú is a typical semi-arid climate (Köppen: *BSk*).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] The comprehensive public high school is Española Valley High School.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] "Abiquiu" is the title of an episode of *Breaking Bad*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abiquiú-new-mexico] During the episode, a flashback shows Jesse Pinkman and Jane Margolis visiting a Georgia O'Keeffe exhibition, presumably the one in Abiquiú.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz was born in Tyumen, Siberia, to Jewish parents.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] He emigrated with his mother to the United States in his early childhood.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] He studied at the National Academy of Design in New York City and the Académie Julian in Paris under Jean-Paul Laurens.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz and his contemporaries later gravitated around photographer Alfred Stieglitz's 291 Gallery, originally titled the Little Galleries of the Photo-Secession, where the forerunners of modern art in America gathered and where many European artists were first exhibited in the United States.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] During the 291 years, Walkowitz worked closely with Stieglitz as well as Arthur Dove, Marsden Hartley, and John Marin (often referred to as "The Stieglitz Quartet").
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz was drawn to art from childhood.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] In a 1958 oral interview with Abram Lerner, he recalled: "When I was a kid, about five years old, I used to draw with chalk, all over the floors and everything...
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] I remember myself as a little boy, of three or four, taking chalk and made drawings." In early adulthood, he worked as a sign painter and began making sketches of immigrants in New York's Jewish ghetto where he lived with his mother.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] He continued to pursue his formal training, and with funds from a friend traveled to Europe in 1906 to attend the Académie Julian.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Through introductions made by Max Weber, it was here that he met Isadora Duncan in Auguste Rodin's studio, the modern American dancer who had captured the attention of the avant-garde.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz went on to produce more than 5,000 drawings of Duncan.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz' approach to art during these years stemmed from European modernist ideas of abstraction, which were slowly infiltrating the American art psyche at the turn of the century.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Like so many artists of the time, Walkowitz was profoundly influenced by the 1907 memorial exhibition of Cézanne's work in Paris at the Salon d'Automne.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Artist Alfred Werner recalled that Walkowitz found Cézanne's pictures to be "simple and intensely human experiences." Working alongside other Stieglitz-supported American modernists, Walkowitz refined his style as an artist and produced various abstract works.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Although Walkowitz drew influences from modern European masters, he was cautious not to be imitative.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Artist and critic Oscar Bluemner recognized this quality in Walkowitz's work, citing the differences between the highly influential writings of Kandinsky and Walkowitz' style.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz first exhibited at the 291 in 1911 after being introduced to Stieglitz through Hartley, and stayed with the gallery until 1917.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] During the 291 years, the climate for modern art in America was harsh.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Until the pivotal Armory Show of 1913 had occurred which Walkowitz was involved with and exhibited in, modern artists importing radical ideas from Europe were received with hostile criticism and a lack of patronage.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Abraham Walkowitz was one of many artists captivated by this new form of movement.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] The Duncan drawings can be interpreted as representations of Walkowitz's loftiest goals.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Composing thousands of these drawings would prove to be one of the most effective outlets for his artistic agenda due to the similarities between the artistic ideals and preferred aesthetic shared by Walkowitz and Duncan.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] He was also able to draw from the same subject repeatedly and extract a different experience with each observation.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Sculptors most readily recognized this trait in Duncan; there was a particular quality of her dance which appeared readily artistic, yet not static.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] In each drawing, a new observation is recorded from the same subject.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] In the *Foreword to A Demonstration of Objective, Abstract, and Non-Objective Art*, Walkowitz wrote in 1913, "I do not avoid objectivity nor seek subjectivity, but try to find an equivalent for whatever is the effect of my relation to a thing, or to a part of a thing, or to an afterthought of it.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] His interest in recording the "keynote" of experience rather than producing an objective representation of a subject is central to the composition of the Duncan drawings.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] The fluidity of the lines function simultaneously as recognizable shapes of the human body, but also trace the pathways of the dancer's movements.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz's dedication to Duncan as a subject extended well past her untimely death in 1927.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] The works reveal shared convictions toward modernism and breaking links with the past.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] In 1958, Walkowitz told Lerner, "She (Duncan) had no laws.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] She did not dance according to the rules.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] It was a body electric, like Walt Whitman.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] One of our greatest men, America's greatest, is Walt Whitman.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] Walkowitz died at the age of 84 at his home in Brooklyn, New York, on January 27, 1965.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/abraham-walkowitz] He was buried in Mount Lebanon Cemetery in Glendale, Queens.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz was born in Hoboken, New Jersey, the first son of German Jewish immigrants Edward Stieglitz (1833–1909) and Hedwig Ann Werner (1845–1922).
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] His father was a lieutenant in the Union Army and worked as a wool merchant.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Alfred Stieglitz, seeing the close relationship of the twins, wished he had a soul mate of his own during his childhood.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz attended Charlier Institute, a Christian school in New York, in 1871.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The following year, his family began spending the summers at Lake George in the Adirondack Mountains, a tradition that continued into Stieglitz's adulthood.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] So that he could qualify for admission to the City College of New York, Stieglitz was enrolled in a public school for his junior year of high school, but found the education inadequate.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1881, Edward Stieglitz sold his company for US $400,000 and moved his family to Europe for the next several years so that his children would receive a better education.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Alfred Stieglitz enrolled in the Real Gymnasium in Karlsruhe.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The next year, Alfred Stieglitz studied mechanical engineering at the Technische Hochschule in Berlin.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He enrolled in a chemistry class taught by Hermann Wilhelm Vogel, a scientist and researcher, who worked on the chemical processes for developing photographs.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In Vogel, Stieglitz found both the academic challenge he needed and an outlet for his growing artistic and cultural interests.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He received an allowance of $1,200 (equivalent to $40,034 in 2025) a year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1884, his parents returned to America, but 20-year-old Stieglitz remained in Germany and collected books on photography and photographers in Europe and the U.S.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He bought his first camera, an 8 × 10 plate film camera, and traveled through the Netherlands, Italy and Germany.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He took photographs of landscapes and workers in the countryside.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Through his self-study, he saw photography as an art form.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1887, he wrote his very first article, "A Word or Two about Amateur Photography in Germany", for the new magazine *Amateur Photographer*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He won first place for his photograph *The Last Joke, Bellagio* from *Amateur Photographer* in 1887.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The next year he won both first and second prizes in the same competition, and his reputation began to spread, as several German and British photographic magazines published his work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1890, his sister Flora died while giving birth, and Stieglitz returned to New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz considered himself an artist, but he refused to sell his photographs.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] His father purchased a small photography business for him so that he could earn a living in his chosen profession.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Because he demanded high quality images and paid his employee high wages, the Photochrome Engraving Company rarely made a profit.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In late 1892, Stieglitz bought his first hand-held camera, a Folmer and Schwing 4×5 plate film camera.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz gained a reputation for his photography and his magazine articles about how photography is a form of art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the spring of 1893, he became co-editor of *The American Amateur Photographer*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In order to avoid the appearance of bias in his opinions and because Photochrome was now printing the photogravures for the magazine, Stieglitz refused to draw a salary.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] On November 16, 1893, the 29-year-old Stieglitz married 20-year-old Emmeline Obermeyer, the sister of his close friend and business associate Joe Obermeyer and granddaughter of brewer Samuel Liebmann.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz later wrote that he did not love Emmy, as she was commonly known, when they were married and that their marriage was not consummated for at least a year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Daughter of a wealthy brewery owner, she had inherited money from her father.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz came to regret his decision to marry Emmy, as she did not share his artistic and cultural interests.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz biographer Richard Whelan summed up their relationship by saying Stieglitz "resented her bitterly for not becoming his twin." Throughout his life Stieglitz maintained a desire for younger women.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz was unanimously elected as one of the first two American members of the British photographic society, The Linked Ring.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz saw this recognition as the impetus he needed to step up his cause of promoting artistic photography in the United States.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In May 1896, the two organizations joined to form The Camera Club of New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Although offered the organization's presidency, he became vice-president.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He developed programs for the club and was involved in all aspects of the organization.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz turned the Camera Club's current newsletter into a magazine, *Camera Notes*, and was given full control over the new publication.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Its first issue was published in July 1897.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] It was soon considered the finest photographic magazine in the world.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Over the next four years Stieglitz used *Camera Notes* to champion his belief in photography as an art form by including articles on art and aesthetics next to prints by some of the leading American and European photographers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He also continued to take his own photographs.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Late in 1896, he hand-pulled the photogravures for a first portfolio of his own work, *Picturesque Bits of New York and Other Studies*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He continued to exhibit in shows in Europe and the U.S., and by 1898 he had gained a solid reputation as a photographer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He was paid $75 (equivalent to $2,903 in 2025) for his favorite print, *Winter – Fifth Avenue*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] On September 27, 1898, Stieglitz's daughter, Katherine "Kitty", was born.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Using Emmy's inheritance, the couple hired a governess, cook and a chambermaid.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz worked at the same pace as before the birth of his daughter, and as a result, the couple predominantly lived separate lives under the same roof.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In May 1899, Stieglitz was given a one-man exhibition, consisting of eighty-seven prints, at the Camera Club.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The strain of preparing for this show, coupled with the continuing efforts to produce *Camera Notes*, took a toll on Stieglitz's health.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] To lessen his burden he brought in his friends Joseph Keiley and Dallet Fuguet, neither of whom were members of the Camera Club, as associate editors of *Camera Notes*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Upset by this intrusion from outsiders, not to mention their own diminishing presence in the Club's publication, many of the older members of the Club began to actively campaign against Stieglitz's editorial authority.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz spent most of 1900 finding ways to outmaneuver these efforts, embroiling him in protracted administrative battles.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Due to the continued strain of managing the Camera Club, by the following year he collapsed in the first of several mental breakdowns.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He spent much of the summer at the family's Lake George home, Oaklawn, recuperating.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] When he returned to New York, he announced his resignation as editor of *Camera Notes*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Photographer Eva Watson-Schütze urged him to establish an exhibition that would be judged solely by photographers who, unlike painters and other artists, knew about photography and its technical characteristics.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz was not only declaring a secession from the general artistic restrictions of the era, but specifically from the official oversight of the Camera Club.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He began formulating a plan to publish a completely independent magazine of pictorial photography to carry forth the artistic standards of the Photo-Secessionist.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] By July, he had fully resigned as editor of *Camera Notes*, and one month later he published a prospectus for a new journal he called *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He was determined it would be "the best and most sumptuous of photographic publications".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The first issue was printed four months later, in December 1902, and like all of the subsequent issues it contained hand-pulled photogravures, critical writings on photography, aesthetics and art, and reviews and commentaries on photographers and exhibitions.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz was a perfectionist, and it showed in every aspect of *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He advanced the art of photogravure printing by demanding unprecedentedly high standards for the prints in *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The visual quality of the gravures was so high that when a set of prints failed to arrive for a Photo-Secession exhibition in Brussels, a selection of gravures from the magazine was hung instead.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Most viewers assumed they were looking at the original photographs.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Throughout 1903, Stieglitz published *Camera Work* and worked to exhibit his own work and that of the Photo-Secessionists while dealing with the stresses of his home life.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Luxembourgish American photographer, Edward Steichen, who later would curate the landmark exhibit The Family of Man, was the most frequently featured photographer in the magazine.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Fuguet, Keiley, and Strauss, Stieglitz's three associate editors at *Camera Notes*, he brought with him to *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Later, he said that he alone individually wrapped and mailed some 35,000 copies of *Camera Work* over the course of its publication.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] On November 25, 1905, the "Little Galleries of the Photo-Secession" opened at 291 Fifth Avenue with one hundred prints by thirty-nine photographers.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Steichen had recommended and encouraged Stieglitz, on his return from Europe, to lease out three rooms across from Steichen's apartment that the pair felt would be perfect to exhibit photography.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The gallery became an instant success, with almost fifteen thousand visitors during its first season and, more importantly, print sales that totaled nearly $2,800, more than half of those sales of Steichen's work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz continued to focus his efforts on photography, at the expense of his family.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Emmy, who hoped she would one day earn Stieglitz's love, continued giving him an allowance from her inheritance.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Two months later the 42-year-old Stieglitz met 28-year-old artist Pamela Colman Smith, who wished to have her drawings and watercolors shown at his gallery.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He decided to show her work because he thought it would be "highly instructive to compare drawings and photographs in order to judge photography's possibilities and limitations".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Her show opened in January 1907, with far more visitors to the gallery than any of the previous photography shows, and soon all of her exhibited works were sold.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz, hoping to capitalize on the popularity of the show, took photographs of her art work and issued a separate portfolio of his platinum prints of her work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the late spring of 1907, Stieglitz collaborated on a series of photographic experiments with his friend Clarence H.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] They took several dozen photographs of two clothed and nude models and printed a selection using unusual techniques, including toning, waxing and drawing on platinum prints.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He made less than $400 for the year due to declining *Camera Work* subscriptions and the gallery's low profit margin.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] While on his way to Europe, Stieglitz took what is recognized not only as his signature image but also as one of the most important photographs of the 20th century: *The Steerage*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz deliberately interspersed exhibitions of what he knew would be controversial art, such as Rodin's sexually explicit drawings, with what Steichen called "understandable art", and with photographs.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] This is thought to have been the first major show in the U.S. in which photographers were given equal ranking with painters.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] For most of 1908 and 1909, Stieglitz spent his time creating shows at 291 and publishing *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] There were no photographs taken during this period that appear in the definitive catalog of his work, *Alfred Stieglitz: The Key Set*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1910, Stieglitz was invited by the director of the Albright Art Gallery to organize a major show of the best of contemporary photography.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Although an announcement of an open competition for the show was printed in *Camera Work*, the fact that Stieglitz would be in charge of it generated a new round of attacks against him.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] An editorial in *American Photography* magazine claimed that Stieglitz could no longer "perceive the value of photographic work of artistic merit which does not conform to a particular style which is so characteristic of all exhibitions under his auspices.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Half a generation ago this school [the Photo-Secession] was progressive, and far in advance of its time.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Throughout 1911 and early 1912, Stieglitz organized ground-breaking modern art exhibits at 291 and promoted new art along with photography in the pages of *Camera Work*.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] By the summer of 1912, he was so enthralled with non-photographic art that he published an issue of *Camera Work* (August 1912) devoted solely to Matisse and Picasso.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In late 1912, painters Walter Pach, Arthur B.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Davies and Walt Kuhn organized a modern art show, and Stieglitz lent a few modern art pieces from 291 to the show.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He also agreed to be listed as an honorary vice-president of the exhibition along with Claude Monet, Odilon Redon, Mabel Dodge and Isabella Stewart Gardner.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In February 1913, the watershed Armory Show opened in New York, and soon modern art was a major topic of discussion throughout the city.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He saw the popularity of the show as a vindication of the work that he had been sponsoring at 291 for the past five years.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He mounted an exhibition of his own photographs at 291 to run at the same time as the Armory Show.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In January 1916, suffragist Anita Pollitzer showed Stieglitz a set of charcoal drawings by Georgia O'Keeffe.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz was so taken by her art that without meeting O'Keeffe or even getting her permission to show her works he made plans to exhibit her work at 291.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The first that O'Keeffe heard about any of this was from another friend who saw her drawings in the gallery in late May of that year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] She finally met Stieglitz after going to 291 and chastising him for showing her work without her permission.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Soon thereafter O'Keeffe met Paul Strand, and for several months she and Strand exchanged increasingly romantic letters.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] When Strand told his friend Stieglitz about his new yearning, Stieglitz responded by telling Strand about his own infatuation with O'Keeffe.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Gradually Strand's interest waned, and Stieglitz's escalated.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] By the summer of 1917 he and O'Keeffe were writing each other "their most private and complicated thoughts".
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In early June 1918, O'Keeffe moved to New York from Texas after Stieglitz promised he would provide her with a quiet studio where she could paint.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Within a month he took the first of many nude photographs of her at his family's apartment while his wife Emmy was away, but she returned while their session was still in progress.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] She had suspected something was going on between the two for a while, and told him to stop seeing her or get out.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz left and immediately found a place in the city where he and O'Keeffe could live together.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] They slept separately for more than two weeks.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] By the end of July they were in the same bed together, and by mid-August when they visited Oaklawn "they were like two teenagers in love.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] O'Keeffe was the muse Stieglitz had always wanted.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He photographed O'Keeffe obsessively between 1918 and 1925 in what was the most prolific period in his entire life.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] During this period he produced more than 350 mounted prints of O'Keeffe that portrayed a wide range of her character, moods and beauty.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He shot many close-up studies of parts of her body, especially her hands either isolated by themselves or near her face or hair.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1920, Stieglitz was invited by Mitchell Kennerly of the Anderson Galleries in New York to put together a major exhibition of his photographs.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In early 1921, he hung the first one-man exhibit of his photographs since 1913.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Of the 146 prints he put on view, only 17 had been seen before.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Forty-six were of O'Keeffe, including many nudes, but she was not identified as the model on any of the prints.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] It was in the catalog for this show that Stieglitz made his famous declaration: "I was born in Hoboken.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1922, Stieglitz organized a large show of John Marin's paintings and etching at the Anderson Galleries, followed by a huge auction of nearly two hundred paintings by more than forty American artists, including O'Keeffe.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Energized by this activity, he began one of his most creative and unusual undertakings – photographing a series of cloud studies simply for their form and beauty.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz's mother Hedwig died in November 1922, and as he did with his father he buried his grief in his work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He spent time with Paul Strand and wife, painter Rebecca Salsbury, reviewed the work of another newcomer named Edward Weston and began organizing a new show of O'Keeffe's work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Her show opened in early 1923, and Stieglitz spent much of the spring marketing her work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Eventually twenty of her paintings sold for more than $3,000.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the summer, O'Keeffe once again took off for the seclusion of the Southwest, and for a while Stieglitz was alone with Salsbury at Lake George.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He took a series of nude photos of her, and soon he became infatuated with her.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] They had a brief physical affair before O'Keeffe returned in the fall.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] O'Keeffe could tell what had happened, but since she did not see Stieglitz's new lover as a serious threat to their relationship she let things pass.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Six years later she would have her own affair with Salsbury in New Mexico.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1924, Stieglitz's divorce was finally approved by a judge, and within four months he and O'Keeffe married in a small, private ceremony at Marin's house.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] They went home without a reception or honeymoon.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] O'Keeffe said later that they married in order to help soothe the troubles of Stieglitz's daughter Kitty, who at that time was being treated in a sanatorium for depression and hallucinations.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] For the rest of their lives together, their relationship was, as biographer Benita Eisler characterized it, "a collusion ... a system of deals and trade-offs, tacitly agreed to and carried out, for the most part, without the exchange of a word.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the coming years O'Keeffe would spend much of her time painting in New Mexico, while Stieglitz rarely left New York except for summers at his father's family estate in Lake George in the Adirondacks, his favorite vacation place.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] At the end of 1924, Stieglitz donated 27 photographs to the Boston Museum of Fine Arts.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] It was the first time a major museum included photographs in its permanent collection.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the same year he was awarded the Royal Photographic Society's Progress Medal for advancing photography and received an Honorary Fellowship of the Society.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1925, Stieglitz was invited by the Anderson Galleries to put together one of the largest exhibitions of American art, entitled *Alfred Stieglitz Presents Seven Americans: 159 Paintings, Photographs, and Things, Recent and Never Before Publicly Shown by Arthur G.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Dove, Marsden Hartley, John Marin, Charles Demuth, Paul Strand, Georgia O'Keeffe and Alfred Stieglitz.* Only one small painting by O'Keeffe was sold during the three-week exhibit.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] O'Keeffe accepted an offer by Mabel Dodge to go to New Mexico for the summer.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz took advantage of her time away to begin photographing Dorothy Norman, and he began teaching her the technical aspects of printing as well.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] When Norman had a second child, she was absent from the gallery for about two months before returning on a regular basis.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In early 1929, Stieglitz was told that the building that housed the Room would be torn down later in the year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] After a final show of Demuth's work in May, he retreated to Lake George for the summer, exhausted and depressed.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The Strands raised nearly sixteen thousand dollars for a new gallery for Stieglitz, who reacted harshly, saying it was time for "young ones" to do some of the work he had been shouldering for so many years.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the late fall, Stieglitz returned to New York.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] On December 15, two weeks before his sixty-fifth birthday, he opened "An American Place", the largest gallery he had ever managed.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] It had the first darkroom he had ever had in the city.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Previously, he had borrowed other darkrooms or worked only when he was at Lake George.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He continued showing group or individual shows of his friends Marin, Demuth, Hartley, Dove and Strand for the next sixteen years.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] O'Keeffe received at least one major exhibition each year.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He fiercely controlled access to her works and incessantly promoted her even when critics gave her less than favorable reviews.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Often during this time, they would only see each other during the summer, when it was too hot in her New Mexico home, but they wrote to each other almost weekly with the fervor of soul mates.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1932, Stieglitz mounted a forty-year retrospective of 127 of his works at The Place.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He included all of his most famous photographs, but he also purposely chose to include recent photos of O'Keeffe, who, because of her years in the Southwest sun, looked older than her forty-five years, in comparison to Stieglitz's portraits of his young lover Norman.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] It was one of the few times he acted spitefully to O'Keeffe in public, and it might have been as a result of their increasingly intense arguments in private about his control over her art.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Later that year, he mounted a show of O'Keeffe's works next to some amateurish paintings on glass by Rebecca Salsbury.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He did not publish a catalog of the show, which the Strands took as an insult.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Paul Strand never forgave Stieglitz for that.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He said, "The day I walked into the Photo-Secession 291 [sic] in 1907 was a great moment in my life… but the day I walked out of An American Place in 1932 was not less good.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1936, Stieglitz returned briefly to his photographic roots by mounting one of the first exhibitions of photos by Ansel Adams in New York City.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] The show was successful and David McAlpin bought eight Adams photos.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] He also put on one of the first shows of Eliot Porter's work two years later.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz, considered the "godfather of modern photography", encouraged Todd Webb to develop his own style and immerse himself in the medium.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In the summer of 1946, Stieglitz suffered a fatal stroke and went into a coma.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] O'Keeffe returned to New York and found Dorothy Norman in his hospital room.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Norman left and O'Keeffe was with him when he died.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] According to his wishes, a simple funeral was attended by twenty of his closest friends and family members.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz was cremated, and, with his niece Elizabeth Davidson, O'Keeffe took his ashes to Lake George and "put him where he could hear the water." The day after the funeral, O'Keeffe took control of An American Place.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Stieglitz produced more than 2,500 mounted photographs over his career.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] After his death, O'Keeffe assembled a set of what she considered the best of his photographs that he had personally mounted.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In some cases she included slightly different versions of the same image, and these series are invaluable for their insights about Stieglitz's aesthetic composition.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1949, she donated the first part of what she called the "key set" of 1,317 Stieglitz photographs to the National Gallery of Art in Washington, DC.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 1980, she added to the set another 325 photographs taken by Stieglitz of her, including many nudes.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] Now numbering 1,642 photographs, it is the largest, most complete collection of Stieglitz's work.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 2002 the National Gallery published a two-volume, 1,012-page catalog that reproduced the complete key set along with detailed annotations about each photograph.
[src:alfred-stieglitz/alfred-stieglitz] In 2019, the National Gallery published an updated, Online Edition of the *Alfred Stieglitz Key Set*.
